# Agent skills – use when writing or changing code

This repo includes **agent skills** in **`.agents/skills/`**. When you create or modify code, read and apply the relevant skills so changes follow their guidelines.

## When to use which skill

| When you are… | Read and apply |
|---------------|----------------|
| **Writing or refactoring React components, Next.js pages, or app code** | **vercel-react-best-practices** – performance (async, bundle, server, client, rerenders, rendering, JS). Read `.agents/skills/vercel-react-best-practices/SKILL.md` for the index; use `AGENTS.md` or individual `rules/*.md` for the rule that matches the change (e.g. data fetching → async-*, new component → rerender-*, bundle → bundle-*). |
| **Designing or refactoring component APIs, compound components, or state/context** | **vercel-composition-patterns** – composition, avoid boolean prop proliferation, compound components, React 19. Read `.agents/skills/vercel-composition-patterns/SKILL.md` for the index; use `AGENTS.md` or `rules/*.md` for the matching pattern (e.g. architecture-*, state-*, patterns-*). |
| **Reviewing UI, accessibility, or design** | **web-design-guidelines** – fetch and apply the guidelines per `.agents/skills/web-design-guidelines/SKILL.md`. |

## How to apply

- **Before implementing**: If the task touches React/Next.js behavior or component design, open the relevant **SKILL.md** (and **AGENTS.md** if you need full rule text) and pick the rules that apply to the change.
- **While implementing**: Follow those rules in the code you add or modify (e.g. parallel data fetching, stable callbacks, composition over boolean props).
- **Project conventions first**: Follow `.cursor/rules/` (components, testing, i18n, etc.) as the primary source; use agent skills to align with the extra performance and composition guidelines.
